smoke, although goodness knows how many cigarettes had already been unconsciously consumed. In general, life around him was so opaque and demanded so little effort of him that it sometimes seemed someone — a mysterious, invisible manager — continued to take him from tournament to tournament; but occasionally there were odd moments, such quietness all around, and when you looked out into the corridor — shoes, shoes, shoes, standing at all the doors, and in your ears the roar of loneliness. 